segments.text: I would take the material from the horse that was recently born and then, you know, work on developing cell lines.
And I developed a few cell lines from that, primary cell cultures.
Then I worked on developing some leukocytes, some cell cultures from leukocytes.
And that's what my thesis had to do with, part of my thesis had to do with developing a leukocyte cell culture system.
All right.
Now, how many years of coursework did you take?
Oh, let's see.
I took two years.
Two years.
Yeah.
And was there a time, was there an official process where you submitted a thesis proposal and it was approved by?
Yeah, but I pretty well did that my first year.
So no hang-ups there?
Really, I didn't have any hang-ups whatsoever with my studies, contrary to what happens a lot of time these days.
I pretty well knew what I wanted to do.
I was pretty well guided into...
I was given a lot of freedom to do whatever I wanted to do, but it was pretty well structured.

Gee, just about everybody I came in contact with out there at Haskell.
I mean, as I say, that's the fortunate thing about this.
Well, Wayne Moore, of course, was primary.
Now, you may want to delete this, but Wayne had a lot of emotional problems later on.
In fact, I think he's in an institution now.
Well, I tried to.

Wayne, Leland Grumbles was my chairman.
All right, yeah.

As a matter of fact, I didn't have to.
quite often I would go by and say, you know, I wonder what this, how this would work.

I never had any problem in visiting with him at all.

Or I'd say, you know, I got this idea.
And, you know, it was a,
I guess you'd say a Socrates-like situation where... What were some of the... Well, I didn't have any problems meeting, I mean, I just didn't feel that there were any deadlines.
Were there any steps that you remember, oh, I was glad when I did this and this?
Yeah.
Well, actually, as I look back over, I mean, at the time,

from a pretty dirty source, trying to make cell cultures out of them.

I felt fairly certain was one that infected leukozytes, and later on it's found to be that.

I tried to incubate, put the things in a common method for isolating viruses is to use inbreeding eggs, chicken eggs.

Well, I don't know, I didn't know at the time.
First of all, I didn't know for sure I was dealing with the virus because I couldn't see it.
I didn't have a good system for culturing it, and so I was really sort of playing blind.
And I was beginning to wonder really if I had made an error in selecting this as a problem because it looked like I wasn't gonna get to an endpoint.
Cuz if I couldn't show the virus, I couldn't, I was really frustrated over that.
But there was an element in it that- When did you know that you were going to be able to reach a successful conclusion with that project?
When I started seeing the virus under the electron microscope.
Okay, and that took about how many months or years?
No, it took about eight months, eight or nine months.
And then- Well, there was another element to the project.
See, this disease, it cycles.
So I had kind of the wild idea that this cycling, this fever and so forth, was associated with something, some destruction of cells or

production of something that is unusual to the host and so I started looking for a protean or a component and that's when I was I was trying to visit with with Mac Prescott about this and I and so I had the theory that an abnormal protean was involved in this and so I started trying to isolate it and I used column chromatography and electrophoresis and sure enough did isolate a component that was

it now is recognized there's a immune globulin is referred to as gamma globulin you know it's it now you can recognize it as an abnormal immune globulin while there may have been literature on that at the time I'm not aware I wasn't aware of it and I'm still not aware of it being available being around at that time at any rate

when I saw the virus and when I this this hypothesis kind of kind of fell into place that I'm dealing with that the disease is associated with with the virus number one and that it's associated with an abnormal protean number two that's when boy that was ecstasy because I was really you know I really felt like I was in and as a matter of fact

Wayne was working was working with a procedure for screening for EIA based upon a serologic technique that that we found out later was based upon that abnormal protein and subsequently we didn't publish that see we were just playing in the lab and subsequently someone
His name was Charles Coggins.
He may have been from Missouri.
I'm not sure where he was from, but anyway, he developed what's called the Coggins test, and that's the standard test.
Even today, that's the standard test for screening for this disease.
All right.
Do you remember going into somebody and saying, I found it, I found it?
Oh, yeah.

Finished the dissertation.
What year?
How many years?

Third year.

Now...
Of course, you know.

First, and then?

I was a research associate in June of 67, and then in the fall.
All right, now this will be the last dollar question.
Do you remember what your salary was when you became assistant professor?
Yeah.
Let's see.
It seemed like it was $15,000.
And by then, had you decided yes or no about medical school?
Well, I was really comfortable.

I really felt comfortable, but I was, you know, I still had a, I got to know several of the physicians around town, and I, you know, I got to thinking, gosh, I'd like to be doing what those guys are doing, but

But then, and also I had some people from Plum Island, the lab in Plum Island, which has to do with animal diseases, had contacted me, invited me up to, and this is just out of the blue, invited me up to talk about my EIA work and that sort of thing.
But, yeah, I was still thinking about medical school, but I still...
I was aware of the fact that I had two children and another one on the way, and we still weren't, I didn't explore the possibilities.
There probably were a number of financial assistantships, but that went further and further back in my mind.
When you joined the department as an assistant professor, were you the only one without a DVM?
Well, shortly afterwards, Jim Grimes followed me, and he was the other one.
Okay.

Did anybody ever... Yep, yep, yep, yep.
Quite often, sometimes.
Not a lot of times.

No, sometimes pretty serious.

About how many faculty were in veterinary microbiology then?
Let's see.
Archie Flowers, there was about...
Seven.
Seven.
And Leland Grumbles was the chairman.
And were there any, was the College of Veterinary Medicine going through any kinds of trauma or?

Yeah, as a matter of fact, in, let's see, in 69, the first time that the vet school came up for accreditation while I was there, and I believe that was in 69, it looked like that Al Price was going to have to step down.
Because they were, the vet school was kind of under the gun.
Let's see, Texas Tech was also wanting to be a vet school, and Governor- Preston Smith, from Lubbock.
From Lubbock, was really pressing to make it.
So these things kind of really put a lot of
pressure on the administration.
I mean, you know, I was just sort of a bystander, but, you know, the possibility of another vet school, the problems
I'm not sure where there's a, I don't know the details on the accreditation issue because I wasn't in the thing, but there was some concern about accreditation at that time.
And there was some concern about Al as a, whether he'd been there long enough or that maybe it was time for him to move on.
I don't know what, and I'm not, that was all hearsay at that time, so
of the situation, but there was a lot of turmoil.
By then, were there some women in that school?
In 69, I believe it was 69, the first woman came in.
Do you remember?
Yes.
Do I remember anything?
Yes, yes.
What was it like when the first women came?
Well, actually, well, the young lady's name was Sonya.
Gosh, I can't remember her last name.
When you think of it, let me know.
I will, yeah.
Because I'd love to interview her.
She would be excellent to, yeah.
What was it really like?

What did the faculty in general think about female?
Whoa, whoa.

They would not have.
They would have voted no?
Yeah.

What would they, if they had voted no?
what would they have felt about admitting blacks to vet school?
Oh, definitely not.
There's a kind of a sick story about that issue.
Let's see, this was 67.
You know, we had departmental faculty meetings on a weekly basis.
And one of the faculty members who held a joint appointment in another, in the animal science department,
made a, to me, a very distasteful comment.
And I'm saying this because this kind of gives you the flavor of the times, and it probably was throughout much of the saddle.
When Martin Luther King was doing his thing about, you know,
He said, I heard one of those guys said that that negro is gonna get all us niggers killed.
And boy, a lot of people laughed over that.
And there were some of us that were really disgusted with that situation.
And I don't really know why we had

or why I was not, but I wasn't.
This just really bothered me.
So that kind of gives you the black students, black applicants would not have made it at that time, in my opinion.
How long was it before you had a female in one of your sections?

No, I never felt that.

How were they?
Well, like a real high efficiency machine.
I mean, they really had everything laid out.

We had meetings once a week.
We had updates on whatever.
